# The Continuity Layer After Memory

**Subtitle:** The Mayorga Mnemosyne AI Continuity Framework for AI Systems That Preserve Meaning Over Time
**Author:** Francisco J. Mayorga, Jr.
**Version:** v1.0
**Status:** Public essay
**Canonical URL:** https://franciscomayorga.com/essays/the-continuity-layer-after-memory

## Summary

This essay introduces the Mayorga Mnemosyne AI Continuity Framework as the governed continuity layer after memory, retrieval, larger context windows, and AI-maintained knowledge bases.

It argues that AI systems are beginning to move beyond disposable prompts toward memory systems, LLM Wikis, agent memory, and knowledge-compounding workflows. However, memory is not continuity. Retrieval is not continuity. A wiki is not continuity.

The missing layer is governed continuity: the ability to preserve meaning, evidence, decisions, assumptions, definitions, contradiction handling, canon status, human review, and justified change across time.

## Framework Position

This essay is part of Francisco J. Mayorga, Jr.’s ongoing public work on the Mayorga Mnemosyne AI Continuity Framework.

Core framing:

> AI proposes. Humans govern. Mnemosyne preserves.

